# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: conservation-international
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] US$5 billion in funding for a project called the "Protecting Our Planet Challenge" was announced for the initiative in September 2021.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] In December 2022, 30 by 30 was agreed at the COP15 meeting of the Convention on Biological Diversity, and became a target of the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] This includes the G7 and European Union.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] The initiative has attracted controversy over indigenous rights issues.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] As of May 2026, 17.3% of terrestrial land and inland waters and 9.8% of marine areas are protected.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] Including OECM's (Other Effective Area-based Conservation Measures) the percent of protected areas are 18.4% of terrestrial and inland waters and 10.0% of marine areas.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] The European Commission's Biodiversity strategy for 2030 was proposed on May 20, 2020, as the European Union's contribution to a post-2020 global biodiversity framework.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] The plan includes turning 30% of EU territory to protected area by 2030 and 10% to strictly protected area.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] However as of 2023 EU is not on track to meet the targets.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] The biodiversity strategy is a core part of the European Green Deal, and also intended to support green recovery from the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] In July 2023 after many debates the European parliament adopted a version of the Nature restoration law, aiming to restore nature on 20% of the territory of the European Union by 2030.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] In 2024, the European Union passed a nature restoration law aiming to restore 20% of degraded ecosystems by 2030 and 100% by 2050.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] On January 27, 2021, President Joe Biden issued an executive order on "Tackling the Climate Crisis at Home and Abroad".
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] Participating federal agencies included the U.S.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] Department of Commerce, and Council on Environmental Quality.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] The order also established a California Biodiversity Collaborative composed of representatives of government agencies, Native tribes, experts, and other stakeholders.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] The official report, *Pathways to 30x30 California*, was issued by the California Natural Resources Agency on 22 April 2022.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] Implementation of the 30 by 30 target has progressed unevenly, and researchers caution that simply increasing the extent of protected areas is not sufficient to halt biodiversity loss.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] Some conservationists argue that the 30% figure lacks a clear scientific justification and risks being treated as a symbolic or political benchmark rather than a threshold grounded in ecological evidence.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] At the same time, other researchers and advocacy groups contend that 30% may in fact be too low to secure long‑term ecological integrity, and point to proposals such as the "Half‑Earth" concept, which calls for roughly 50% of terrestrial and marine realms to be conserved in some form.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] A further concern relates to the quality and effectiveness of protection once areas are designated.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] Researchers and NGOs have highlighted the persistence of so‑called "paper parks": protected areas that exist in law but lack adequate funding, staffing or enforcement, allowing activities such as poaching, illegal logging, or unregulated development to continue.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] Modelling work by Kuempel et al. suggests that, for exploited species, improving enforcement and management within existing protected areas can in many cases deliver greater conservation benefits than simply expanding the network’s total area without a corresponding increase in resources.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] Taken together, this literature underlines that meeting percentage‑based targets without adequate governance capacity risks diluting scarce conservation resources.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] Other research has examined conditions under which expanding protected areas can still be beneficial even when management budgets do not increase.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] Their results suggest that, in landscapes where human pressures are spatially clumped near reserve boundaries, strategically increasing the size of protected areas can create more secure habitat refuges even without proportional increases in staffing or enforcement.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] In practice, the 30 by 30 commitment has also prompted debate over how "protected" or "conserved" areas are defined for monitoring and reporting purposes.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] Implementation of the 30 by 30 target has also raised concerns about “green grabbing” and green colonialism in the way new protected and conserved areas may be established.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] Similar critiques have been echoed by human rights organisations and researchers who argue that percentage-based conservation targets can replicate earlier "fortress conservation" models if they are implemented through top-down land designations that disregard customary tenure and existing uses.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] More broadly, some Indigenous organisations have criticised the way 30 by 30 has been promoted and negotiated, arguing that it risks appropriating Indigenous lands under the guise of biodiversity conservation.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] The COP15 included 196 parties in negotiations, with competing views regarding the adoption of the 30 by 30 target being wide-spread and well documented.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] The resulting agreement of the conference, the Convention on Biological Diversity, was signed by every party, with the exception of two: the United States and the Vatican.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] Towards the end of the talks, a negotiator from Democratic Republic of the Congo raised objections to the agreement, citing a lack of funding separate from the current Global Environment Facility (GEF).
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] After a delay, COP15 president and Chinese environment minister Huang Runqiu overruled the objection due to a legal technicality, resulting in the passage of the agreement.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] Delegates from the DRC, Cameroon, and Uganda were reportedly displeased with the outcome.
[src:conservation-international/30-by-30] After the agreement was passed, the DRC's government announced that it would not recognize it as valid.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] A **501(c)(3) organization** is a United States corporation, trust, unincorporated association, or other type of organization exempt from federal income tax under section 501(c)(3) of Title 26 of the United States Code.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] It is one of the 29 types of 501(c) nonprofit organizations in the U.S.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] The 501(c)(3) exemption applies also for any non-incorporated community chest, fund, cooperating association or foundation organized and operated exclusively for those purposes.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] There are also supporting organizations—often referred to in shorthand form as *Friends of* organizations.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] 26 U.S.C. § 170 provides a deduction for federal income tax purposes, for some donors who make charitable contributions to most types of 501(c)(3) organizations, among others.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Regulations specify which such deductions must be verifiable to be allowed (e.g., receipts for donations of $250 or more).
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] The basic requirement of obtaining tax-exempt status is that the organization is specifically limited in powers to purposes that the IRS classifies as tax-exempt purposes.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] This limiting of the powers is crucial to obtaining tax exempt status with the IRS and then on the state level.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Organizations acquire 501(c)(3) tax exemption by filing IRS Form 1023.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] As of 2006, the form must be accompanied by an $850 filing fee if the yearly gross receipts for the organization are expected to average $10,000 or more.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] If yearly gross receipts are expected to average less than $10,000, the filing fee is reduced to $400.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] The IRS released a software tool called Cyber Assistant in 2013, which was succeeded by Form 1023-EZ in 2014.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] There is an alternative way for an organization to obtain status if an organization has applied for a determination and either there is an actual controversy regarding a determination or the Internal Revenue Service has failed to make a determination.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Prior to December 30, 1969, nonprofit organizations could declare themselves to be tax-exempt under Section 501(c)(3) without first obtaining Internal Revenue Service recognition by filing Form 1023 and receiving a determination letter.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] A nonprofit organization that did so prior to that date could still be subject to challenge of its status by the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] An individual may not take a tax deduction on gifts made to a 501(c)(3) organization that is organized and operated exclusively for the testing for public safety.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] In the case of tuition fees paid to a private 501(c)(3) school or a church school, the payments are not tax-deductible charitable contributions because they are payments for services rendered to the payee or the payee's children.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] The payments are not tax-deductible charitable contributions even if a significant portion of a church school's curriculum is religious education.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] For a payment to be a tax-deductible charitable contribution, it must be a voluntary transfer of money or other property with no expectation of procuring financial benefit equal to the transfer amount.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Before donating to a 501(c)(3) organization, a donor can consult the searchable online IRS list of charitable organizations to verify that the organization qualifies to receive tax-deductible charitable contributions.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Consumers may file IRS Form 13909, with documentation, to complain about inappropriate or fraudulent (i.e., fundraising, political campaigning, lobbying) activities by any 501(c)(3) organization.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Most 501(c)(3) must disclose the names and addresses of certain large donors to the Internal Revenue Service on their annual returns, but this information is not required to be made available to the public, unless the organization is an independent foundation.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Churches are generally exempt from this reporting requirement.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Every 501(c)(3) organization must make available for public inspection its application for tax-exemption, including its Form 1023 or Form 1023-EZ and any attachments, supporting documents, and follow-up correspondence with the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Annual returns must be publicly available for a three-year period beginning with the due date of the return, including any extension of time for filing.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] The Internal Revenue Service provides information about specific 501(c)(3) organizations through its Tax Exempt Organization Search online.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] A private nonprofit organization, GuideStar, provides information on 501(c)(3) organizations.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] ProPublica's Nonprofit Explorer provides copies of each organization's Form 990 and, for some organizations, audited financial statements.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] WikiCharities, is a nonprofit database of nonprofits and charities by name, location, and topic, that allows each organization to report its financials, leadership, contacts, and other activities.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] However, Open990 was a searchable database of information about organizations that had to shut down due to IRS delays in posting information online.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations are prohibited from supporting political candidates, as a result of the Johnson Amendment enacted in 1954.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations are subject to limits on lobbying, having a choice between two sets of rules establishing an upper bound for their lobbying activities.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations risk loss of their tax-exempt status if these rules are violated.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] An organization that loses its 501(c)(3) status due to being engaged in political activities cannot subsequently qualify for 501(c)(3) status.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] As a result, it is common for 501(c)(3) organizations to have affiliated nonprofits that are classified as 501(c)(4) organizations, allowing the affiliate to engage in political activity without threatening 501(c)(3) status.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Churches must meet specific requirements to obtain and maintain tax-exempt status; these are outlined in "IRS Publication 1828: Tax Guide for Churches and Religious Organizations".
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] This guide outlines activities allowed and not allowed by churches under the 501(c)(3) designation.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Schools for the preparation of its ministers.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Having an established congregation served by an organized ministry is of central importance.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Points 4, 6, 8, 11, 12, and 13 are also especially important.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Nevertheless, the 14-point list is a guideline; it is not intended to be all-encompassing, and other facts and circumstances may be relevant factors.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Although there is no definitive definition of a church for Internal Revenue Code purposes, in 1986 the United States Tax Court said that "A church is a coherent group of individuals and families that join together to accomplish the religious purposes of mutually held beliefs.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] The United States Tax Court has stated that, while a church can certainly broadcast its religious services by radio, radio broadcasts themselves do not constitute a congregation unless there is a group of people physically attending those religious services.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] A church can conduct worship services in various specific locations rather than in one official location.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] A church may have a significant number of people associate themselves with the church on a regular basis, even if the church does not have a traditional established list of individual members.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] In order to qualify as a tax-exempt church, church activities must be a significant part of the organization's operations.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] An organization whose operations include a substantial nonexempt commercial purposes, such as operating restaurants and grocery stores in a manner consistent with a particular religion's religious beliefs does not qualify as a tax-exempt church.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] In practice, hospital policies often don't cover outside contracted physicians or narrowly defined medically necessary services, leaving patients who technically qualify for charity care still responsible for significant medical bills.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Organizations described in section 501(c)(3) are prohibited from conducting political campaign activities to intervene in elections to public office.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Since section 501(c)(3)'s political-activity prohibition was enacted, "commentators and litigants have challenged the provision on numerous constitutional grounds", such as freedom of speech, vagueness, and equal protection and selective prosecution.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Historically, Supreme Court decisions, such as *Regan v.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Taxation with Representation of Washington*, suggested that the Court, if it were to squarely examine the political-activity prohibition of § 501(c)(3), would uphold it against a constitutional challenge.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] However, some have suggested that a successful challenge to the political activities prohibition of Section 501(c)(3) might be more plausible in light of *Citizens United v.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] In contrast to the prohibition on political campaign interventions by all section 501(c)(3) organizations, public charities (but not private foundations) may conduct a limited amount of lobbying to influence legislation.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Although the law states that "no substantial part" of a public charity's activities can go to lobbying, charities with large budgets may lawfully expend a million dollars (under the "expenditure" test) or more (under the "substantial part" test) per year on lobbying.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] The Internal Revenue Service has never defined the term "substantial part" with respect to lobbying.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] To establish a safe harbor for the "substantial part" test, the United States Congress enacted §501(h), called the Conable election after its author, Representative Barber Conable.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] The section establishes limits based on operating budget that a charity can use to determine if it meets the substantial test.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] This changes the prohibition against direct intervention in partisan contests only for lobbying.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] The organization is now presumed in compliance with the substantiality test if they work within the limits.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] The Conable election requires a charity to file a declaration with the IRS and file a functional distribution of funds spreadsheet with their Form 990.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] IRS form 5768 is required to make the Conable election.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to conduct some or all of its charitable activities outside the United States.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to award grants to foreign charitable organizations if the grants are intended for charitable purposes and the grant funds are subject to the 501(c)(3) organization's control.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Additional procedures are required of 501(c)(3) organizations that are private foundations.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] Donors' contributions to a 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible only if the contribution is for the use of the 501(c)(3) organization, and that the 501(c)(3) organization is not merely serving as an agent or conduit of a foreign charitable organization.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] The 501(c)(3) organization's management should review the grant application from the foreign organization, decide whether to award the grant based on the intended use of the funds, and require continuous oversight based on the use of funds.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] If the donor imposes a restriction or earmark that the contribution must be used for foreign activities, then the contribution is deemed to be for the foreign organization rather than the 501(c)(3) organization, and the contribution is not tax-deductible.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] The purpose of the grant to the foreign organization cannot include endorsing or opposing political candidates for elected office in any country.
[src:conservation-international/501-c-3-organization] If a 501(c)(3) organization sets up and controls a foreign subsidiary to facilitate charitable work in a foreign country, then donors' contributions to the 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible even if intended to fund the foreign charitable activities.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] The **French Development Agency** (**French: *Agence française de développement***, **AFD**) is a public French financial institution that supports and complements France's diplomacy.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] Active in Africa, Asia, the Middle East, Latin America, the Indo-Pacific, the Caribbean, and France's overseas territories, AFD finances and supports projects that aim to improve living conditions, foster economic growth, and protect the planet.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] Its 2,600 staff members are based in Paris, Marseille, and a network of 85 offices worldwide.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] AFD's origins go back to the Caisse Centrale de la France Libre (CCFL), created by Charles de Gaulle on 2 December 1941 and successively renamed the Caisse Centrale de la France d'Outre-Mer (CCFOM) in February 1944 and the Caisse Centrale de Coopération Économique (CCCE) in 1958.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] By 1967, the CCCE had lost all the money-issuing duties that had been at the origin of the CCFL, but had expanded the development financing that the CCFOM had acquired in 1944.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] In 1992, the CCCE was renamed the Caisse Française de Développement.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] With the reform of French development cooperation in 1998, the CFD became *Agence Française de Développement*.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] In addition to a marked increase in its financing, between 2001 and 2010, there was a diversification in the financial instruments used by AFD: grants, of course, but also highly “concessional” loans or loans without interest subsidies, investment funds, guarantee funds and partnerships.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] AFD can provide loan recipients with liquidity to finance, at attractive rates – due to the AAA rating, the highest for long-term issuances, given to AFD by the international rating agencies –, their investment policies or programs when markets are unable to meet their needs.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] In 2013, Anne Paugam took over from Dov Zerah as CEO.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] In 2014, The Act on Development and International Solidarity recognized the importance of the work conducted by AFD towards France's international commitments.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] In 2015, Gaël Giraud became AFD's Chief Economist.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] In 2016, Rémy Rioux took over as CEO from Anne Paugam.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] A new French law enacted in 2021 established the AFD Group, bringing together Proparco, Expertise France, and AFD.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] As a specialized credit institution, AFD is subject to banking law, particularly in the field of risk sharing.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] The Government has entrusted it with the role of the main operator for France's cooperation policy.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] It thereby combines the functions of development bank and implementing agency for France's Official Development Assistance policy.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] AFD has a contract of objectives and policies with the state and implements the orientations defined by the Inter-ministerial Committee for International Cooperation and Development (CICID), chaired by the Prime Minister.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] In overseas France, AFD conducts a policy, on behalf of the state, to support public authorities and finance the economy.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] This mandate was reaffirmed during the first Inter-ministerial Committee for Overseas France, chaired by the French president, which was held in November 2009.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] Its board of directors comprises a chairperson and 16 members appointed by a decree, including 6 representatives of the State: Ministry of the Economy, Industry and Digital Affairs, Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Development, Ministry of the Interior, Ministry of Overseas France.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] The French Development Agency (AFD) implements the policy defined by the French Government.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] It works to combat poverty and promote sustainable development.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] It achieves this by financing and supporting projects that improve living conditions for populations, promote economic growth and protect the planet.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] In 2014, AFD allocated EUR 8.1bn to finance projects, including EUR 6.35bn in developing countries and EUR 1.55bn for overseas France.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] In 2014, AFD allocated some EUR 767m to education and health and invested over EUR 633m in water and sanitation programs.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] Projects related to territorial development benefited from over EUR 4bn, i.e. almost half AFD's commitments, with projects in the energy, transport and telecommunications sectors in rural and urban areas.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] AFD also operates in emerging countries for issues related to the protection of the environment and energy management.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] In a crosscutting manner to these sectors, in 2014, AFD earmarked 53% of its international activity for the fight against climate change, *i.e.* EUR 2.8bn, which financed development projects that also have a positive impact on the climate.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] AFD, *via* the projects it finances and several initiatives, is gearing up for the 21st Conference of the Parties (COP21) to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC).
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] AFD has been working for over sixty years to promote development in Southern countries and the French overseas territories.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] AFD's strategy is guided by sustainable development.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] Its operations are in line with the Millennium Development Goals, at the intersection of the objectives of economic growth, poverty reduction and environmental conservation.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] A wide range of financial and technical instruments meet the different needs of countries: grants, guarantees, equity investments, subsidized loans, loans on market terms and technical assistance.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] It develops financial and intellectual partnerships with other donors and contributes, in conjunction with its supervisory authorities, to public policymaking and to France's influence in the development sphere.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] In Latin America and the Caribbean, AFD promotes sustainable and equitable development through green and inclusive growth.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] There are a number of projects to fight climate change, for urban development, as well as projects to promote social convergence.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] Sub-Saharan Africa is the priority region for France's public development policy.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] In 2014, AFD invested EUR 2.95bn in the region, i.e.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] Among the many projects, a number focus on promoting access to essential services, the growth of sustainable cities, the development of infrastructure, family farming and job-creating enterprises, as well as on the preservation of natural resources.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] In Asia, AFD works to promote environmental and regional balances, with a focus on projects that limit the environmental footprint of cities or contribute to regional convergence.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] AFD supports the region's political and economic transition, with a focus on promoting Euro-Mediterranean integration, territorial development and job creation.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] The AFD also funds restoration works, such as that of the Saint Hilarion monastery which the AFD funded in order to have the Byzantine-era site inscribed in the UNESCO World Heritage Sites list.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] Since 1946, AFD has had a public service mandate to provide a reference public service provision for credit and social housing.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] In 2014, overseas France accounted for 19% of AFD's activity, i.e.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] AFD conducts several types of action in overseas France.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] Its activities are based on the following areas: financing and assisting public policies, advisory services for local authorities, promoting business competitiveness and job creation, supporting regional integration and action for sustainable development.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] This involves financing and supporting projects that improve living conditions for populations and promote economic growth, while preserving the environment.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] Thanks to its financing, its expertise and its knowledge production, it assists the local public sector, finances companies, housing and urban development, and supports regional cooperation.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] It fulfills this mandate through nine agencies throughout the overseas territories: French Guiana, French Polynesia, Guadeloupe, Martinique, Mayotte, New Caledonia, Réunion, Saint Pierre and Miquelon, Wallis and Futuna.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] In the overseas departments (DOM), in Saint Martin, Saint Barthélemy and Saint Pierre and Miquelon, AFD also represents the public investment bank Bpifrance, which finances the creation, innovation, investments and international development of French SMEs.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] AFD is the reference shareholder in seven social housing companies (Simar in Martinique, Sic in New Caledonia, Sig in Guadeloupe, SIDR in Réunion, Siguy and Simko in French Guiana and Sim in Mayotte).
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] These property companies promote, manage and build social housing.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] Finally, it provides part of the staff of the note-issuing banks, Institut d'Emission d'Outre-mer and Institut d'Emission des Départements d'Outre-mer.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] Knowledge production is a major activity for AFD and aims to contribute to the definition of the public policies of France and its partners.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] It has become an essential complement to the financial and technical tools.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] AFD's knowledge production started to play an important role in the 2000s.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] This drive for knowledge production is based on the organization of seminars and conferences, training given by CEFEB, a studies and research program, and the establishment of partnerships with academic and research institutes.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] In 2007, AFD was called into question for its support for French companies suspected of contributing to deforestation in Central Africa.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] However, no legal proceedings were brought against AFD.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] AFD has strict procedures during project appraisal for impact control and measurement in terms of social and environmental responsibility.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] It has provided EUR 900,000 of financing to the Central Africa Forest Commission (COMIFAC), which is responsible for guiding, coordinating, harmonizing and taking decisions in terms of the conservation and sustainable management of forest ecosystems.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] Joyandet, French Secretary of State for Cooperation and Francophonie from March 2008 to July 2010, criticized the Chief Executive Officer at the time, Mr.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] Severino, for AFD's emergency-oriented approach, without a long term-vision and a certain lack of scope.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] However, the Minister's remarks did not gain wide consensus among the development community.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] According to the Cameroon National Anti-corruption Commission (CONAC), two front companies, including one controlled by AFD, have been suspected of fraud.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] In December 2013, CONAC presented its 2012 activity report in Yaoundé, indicating that over CFA 113bn had been misappropriated from the cotton development company (SODECOTON) between 2002 and 2011.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] In December 2021, created under the name Caisse centrale de la France libre in 1941, the public financial institution could change its name again in the coming months, 80 years after its launch.
[src:conservation-international/agence-française-de-développement] Or a project in the process of reflection, which also includes an overhaul of its operation and its development policy, which "appear unsuitable in relation to our experience", according to its director Rémy Rioux.
[src:conservation-international/alto-mayo-protection-forest] The **Alto Mayo Protection Forest** (Spanish: *Bosque de Protección Alto Mayo*) is an area of protected forest land in northern Peru.
[src:conservation-international/alto-mayo-protection-forest] It is located in Rioja and Moyobamba provinces within the region of San Martin, with a small part in Rodriguez de Mendoza province, in the region of Amazonas.
[src:conservation-international/alto-mayo-protection-forest] This area preserves a portion of the tropical yungas forest in the upper Mayo River basin, while protecting soil and water from erosion by deforestation, as the area is the water supply of populations in the Mayo valley.
[src:conservation-international/alto-mayo-protection-forest] In 1963, the Peruvian government granted protection over the area, declaring it the **Alto Mayo National Forest** by Law No 442; however, in the 1970s, many people started to occupy the area and clear the pristine forests.
[src:conservation-international/alto-mayo-protection-forest] Also, workers who built a road across the national forest began to hunt the yellow-tailed woolly monkey for its meat.
[src:conservation-international/alto-mayo-protection-forest] The government tried to control the situation by modifying the original law, declaring only the forests in the upper part of the valley to be under protection; the rest of the former national forest was declared land for free agricultural use.
[src:conservation-international/alto-mayo-protection-forest] The rediscovery of the yellow-tailed woolly monkey in 1974 in nearby areas attracted efforts of research and conservation to the national forest.
[src:conservation-international/alto-mayo-protection-forest] In 1977, the local office of the Ministry of Agriculture attempted to establish boundaries and a protection category for the forest, but the initiative was forgotten.
[src:conservation-international/alto-mayo-protection-forest] In 1979, a main road connecting the eastern forest lands with the Pacific coast (Carretera Marginal de la Selva) was opened.
[src:conservation-international/alto-mayo-protection-forest] The same year, another free use zone was declared on land proposed for conservation within the national forest.
[src:conservation-international/alto-mayo-protection-forest] Between 1974 and 1983, several research projects on local fauna and forest ecology were conducted, all reaching the conclusion that the area should be given conservation priority.
[src:conservation-international/alto-mayo-protection-forest] The initiative for park delimitation and protection was resumed in 1984; the forest was protected by decree in 1987.
[src:conservation-international/alto-mayo-protection-forest] The protected area covers 1,820 square kilometres (450,000 acres) of forest land along the upper River Mayo basin.
[src:conservation-international/alto-mayo-protection-forest] This is a mountainous area, as it is located in the eastern part of the Andes, featuring slope grades greater than 70% in some parts.
[src:conservation-international/alto-mayo-protection-forest] The area and its surroundings are part of the river Mayo upper watershed and eleven of the Mayo's main tributaries originate within the Alto Mayo Protected Forest.
[src:conservation-international/alto-mayo-protection-forest] The **Alto Mayo Protection Forest** protects part of the Peruvian Yungas ecoregion.
[src:conservation-international/alto-mayo-protection-forest] Some of the mammals reported in the area are the yellow-tailed woolly monkey, the spectacled bear, the cougar, the Peruvian night monkey, the Rio Mayo titi and the giant armadillo.
[src:conservation-international/alto-mayo-protection-forest] The main threats to this protected area are: the illegal settlement of farmers inside the forest who clear the land for agriculture; the extraction of wild orchids and animals for sale; timber extraction and unsustainable fishing practices.
[src:conservation-international/alto-mayo-protection-forest] A forest-conservation and climate-mitigation initiative in the protected forest has used conservation agreements linked to voluntary-market REDD+ finance, and has been associated with Conservation International Peru.
[src:conservation-international/american-prairie-foundation] The **American Prairie Foundation** is a nonprofit organization located in the U.S. state of Montana.
[src:conservation-international/american-prairie-foundation] The foundation's objective is to build one of the largest wildlife reserves in the continental United States through a combination of new land acquisition and public land integration into the project, called the American Prairie.
[src:conservation-international/american-prairie-foundation] To accomplish this, the foundation estimates that it must acquire 500,000 acres (2,000 km2) privately, which would then link together over 3,000,000 acres (12,000 km2) of existing public property.
[src:conservation-international/american-prairie-foundation] Russell National Wildlife Refuge is one of the project's anchor properties.
[src:conservation-international/american-prairie-foundation] The American Prairie Foundation (doing business as American Prairie) seeks to create a landscape reminiscent of that seen by the Lewis and Clark Expedition.
[src:conservation-international/american-prairie-foundation] The American Prairie Foundation developed a 7-point scale to evaluate land based on ten ecological conditions including plant diversity, grazing, fire, hydrology and predators to measure the impact of reserve management activities.
[src:conservation-international/american-prairie-foundation] Approximately ten percent of the funding comes from private foundations supporting land conservation and the remaining ninety percent comes from individuals living in 46 states and eight countries.
[src:conservation-international/american-prairie-foundation] Approximately 20% of its donors reside in the state of Montana.
[src:conservation-international/american-prairie-foundation] As of December 2013, they had raised $67.3 million in cash and pledges since 2002.
[src:conservation-international/andasibe-mantadia-national-park] The national park was nominated in 2007 to become part of the World Heritage Site of Rainforests of the Atsinanana.
[src:conservation-international/andasibe-mantadia-national-park] However, its forests were not selected for the final list.
[src:conservation-international/andasibe-mantadia-national-park] This is one of the easiest parks in Madagascar to visit from the capital city, Antananarivo, with a 3-hour drive east on a paved road, Route Nationale 2 (RN 2).
[src:conservation-international/andasibe-mantadia-national-park] While Analamazaotra and park headquarters are short walks from Antsapanana on the RN 2, special transport must be arranged or hired from local hotels to reach Mantadia.
[src:conservation-international/andasibe-mantadia-national-park] Hikes ranging from 1–6 hours are typically available in both parts of the park.
[src:conservation-international/andasibe-mantadia-national-park] A local guide is required for visitors entering either part of the park.
[src:conservation-international/andasibe-mantadia-national-park] The Analamazaotra (or Périnet) Special Reserve (ASR), known locally as *Andasibe* after the nearby village, was once part of the larger Mantadia National Park which also included Maromizaha Classified Forest to the southeast and Anosibe an'ala to the south.
[src:conservation-international/andasibe-mantadia-national-park] However logging and deforestation for farming has resulted in these parks now being isolated.
[src:conservation-international/andasibe-mantadia-national-park] The main threat to this park comes from the disappearance of adjoining habitat outside the park.
[src:conservation-international/andasibe-mantadia-national-park] In 2025, the park was designated as a biosphere reserve by UNESCO.
[src:conservation-international/andasibe-mantadia-national-park] To address the disappearing habitat threat, reserves have been created in the vicinity of Andasibe-Mantadia that balance resource extraction with environmental protection, and attempt to create economic and environmentally preferable alternatives to replacing native forests with eucalyptus and pine.
[src:conservation-international/andasibe-mantadia-national-park] In 2006, the Madagascar Biodiversity Partnership and Omaha's Henry Doorly Zoo & Aquarium, in collaboration with Madagascar National Parks and Eaux et Fôret initiated the Analamazaotra Re-introduction/Translocation (ART) project to reintroduce two endangered species of lemur back into the park.
[src:conservation-international/andasibe-mantadia-national-park] The aim was to take lemurs from threatened areas where habitat loss means the incumbent population is unsustainable, and relocate them to the relative safety of the Analamazaotra Special Reserve.
[src:conservation-international/andasibe-mantadia-national-park] The program followed the IUCN re-introduction/translocation guidelines, with family group monitoring before and after translocation.
[src:conservation-international/andasibe-mantadia-national-park] By 2014, the ART project had reintroduced three groups comprising 26 diademed sifaka and 8 black-and-white ruffed lemur into the park.
[src:conservation-international/andasibe-mantadia-national-park] The project's multi-disciplinary team tracked the reintroduced groups using radio collars, and collected fecal samples to evaluate biomedical, genetic, habitat, nutritional and reproductive characteristics of the lemurs.
[src:conservation-international/andasibe-mantadia-national-park] The project has so far been very successful, and visitors to this popular reserve have been lucky enough to see two generations of babies born at the park.
[src:conservation-international/andasibe-mantadia-national-park] The ART project also helps the local community by education and provides two local guides.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] In 2015, Esteves was accused of obstructing justice.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] In July 2018, he was acquitted by the Federal Court.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] In April 2022, he was reappointed chairman of BTG Pactual.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] He is a board member of Conservation International, Inteli and Council on Foreign Relations.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] André Esteves was born into a middle-class family in Rio de Janeiro, and obtained his bachelor's degree in computer science from the Federal University of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] Esteves has three children, and *The New York Times* writes that "he has driven the same Mercedes pickup for four years and takes only two weeks of vacation a year".
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] Esteves is involved in the wine industry.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] In 2012, he acquired the Italian winery Argiano, located in Montalcino, Tuscany, and in 2013 acquired Quinta da Romaneira in Portugal's Douro Valley.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] Under his ownership, Argiano adopted organic farming practices and sustainability initiatives, including the elimination of single-use plastics by 2019.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] In 2023, the Argiano Brunello di Montalcino 2018 was named “Wine of the Year” by ''Wine Spectator''.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] UBS purchased Pactual in December 2006, and became UBS Pactual.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] Esteves led the Latin American operations and later moved to London, where he served as global head of fixed income, currencies, and commodities.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] June 2008, Esteves left UBS Pactual along with key Brazilian partners to create BTG, a global investment company.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] In April 2009, they purchased Pactual back from UBS for US$2.5 billion.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] He discussed these events an interview for the Creating Emerging Markets project at the Harvard Business School.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] Esteves arrives at his office as early as 6:30 AM and "often calls partners together for meetings as late as 10:00 p.m." He also holds regular study meetings with BTG Pactual directors at his home.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] According to the ''Financial Times'', the firm expanded its operations beyond traditional investment banking into commodities trading, infrastructure, and international markets.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] By the mid-2020s, BTG Pactual had assets under management reported in excess of US$300 billion and expanded its presence beyond Latin America through operations in Europe and North America.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] In September 2023, the bank completed the acquisition of 100% of the share capital of FIS Privatbank in Luxembourg for 21.3 million euros, aiming to expand its wealth management and asset management activities in Europe.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] In June 2024, it announced the acquisition of M.Y.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] Safra Bank in the United States, a transaction finalized in January 2026, granting the institution a banking license to operate directly in the North American market as BTG Pactual Bank.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] Additionally, in October 2025, BTG Pactual proposed a corporate reorganization to incorporate all remaining shares of Banco Pan, resulting in the cancellation of Banco Pan's public company registration and its conversion into a wholly-owned subsidiary.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] In interviews cited by financial media, Esteves has emphasized the strategic importance of commodities, particularly agriculture, stating that Brazil could play a central role in meeting future global food demand.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] Financial media have also reported that BTG Pactual has invested in building a commodities trading platform focused on flows between Latin America and Asia.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] James Crombie of LatinFinance writes that "Esteves supports education and environmental charities".
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] In addition, André Esteves is a member of the Global Board of Advisors of the Council on Foreign Relations.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] He has also supported initiatives, projects, and institutions that aim to improve education, healthcare, and promote the arts in Brazil.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] Institutions like the Universidade de São Paulo, the "Hospital de Câncer de Barretos" and the Museu de Arte Moderna de São Paulo are among those supported by Esteves.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] In April 2020, Esteves and other partners of BTG Pactual announced a donation of 50 million Brazilian reais for COVID-19 pandemic combat projects in Brazil.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] Esteves is also known for his pro-environment activities, most of them in private.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] He is a board member at Conservation International and played an active role supporting the Amazonia Live program, a project to plant one million trees, in partnership with one of the biggest music festivals of the world, Rock in Rio.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] He is part of the 5P Alliance, a group of entrepreneurs, bankers, and doctors who are working on their own to ensure the conservation of the Pantanal biome by acquiring farms in the region to preserve them.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] The goal is to create large ecological corridors and keep the biome as the most preserved in the country.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] André Esteves is the owner of Fazenda Rio Negro, which in 2001 was granted the title of Private Natural Heritage Reserve (RPPN) by the government of Mato Grosso do Sul for having several endangered species such as the giant otter, the marsh deer, and the hyacinth macaw.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] The property was also a filming location for the Brazilian TV series Pantanal.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] In 2021, he founded the Institute of Technology and Leadership (Inteli) with Roberto Sallouti, with the aim of providing higher education for students in the field of Technology, with emphasis on Computing, Business, and Leadership.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] Esteves and his family sponsored the initiative with a donation of US$38 million.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] André Esteves made a significant personal donation to Harvard Business School, in order to renovate the former Baker Hall, located on the campus of Harvard University; now renamed as Esteves Hall, in honor of him.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] This Harvard dormitory is used by the School's Executive Education programs, which annually attract some 10,000 executives from around the globe, many from Esteves' home country, Brazil.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] BTG Pactual, where André Esteves serves as chairman and senior partner, is a Brazilian investment bank and asset management firm.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] Approximately 70% of the company is owned by its partners, fostering an alignment of long-term interests with its stakeholders.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] The bank is also active in proprietary investments (both class of net assets as of non-liquid assets).
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] It is recognized as one of the leading investment banks in emerging markets, the largest independent investment bank and the largest asset manager in Brazil.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] In April 2012, André Esteves was fined €350,000 for insider trading in Italy by Consob.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] They said, that "the 43-year-old Latin American banker bought the shares in November 2007 knowing that the group was planning to enter a joint venture with Brazilian rival JBS." This case was closed and there was no impact to the public offering.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] In 2006, Esteves sold Pactual to UBS for 3.1 billion Swiss francs, and later repurchased the firm in 2009 for 2.5 billion Swiss francs after leaving UBS to establish BTG Pactual.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] Huw Jenkins, who was involved in the 2006 transaction at UBS, later became a senior partner and board member at BTG Pactual in 2010.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] Esteves has been involved in civil proceedings filed in Hong Kong by a former employee; the case received limited media coverage and was reportedly resolved privately.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] Earlier media reports also noted commercial disputes involving corporate investments, such as Sete Participações, and other business dealings in Brazil.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] These matters were primarily civil or commercial in nature, did not result in convictions, and were settled through legal or private means.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] On 25 November 2015, Esteves was arrested as part of a scandal investigation into Petrobras and his bank's dealings with the oil company.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] Three weeks later, on December 17, 2015, Esteves was released from prison.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] BTG's bonds and shares rose 7.7 percent to 15.62 reais at 3:55 p.m. in São Paulo, after gaining as much as 12 percent.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] The company's $1 billion of notes due 2020 rose 3.1 cents to 72.15 cents on the dollar.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] Esteves' attorneys argued that he was only arrested because he's one of the wealthiest people in Brazil, according to court documents filed this month with the supreme court.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] On 27 April 2016, the bank confirmed in a statement that he would be a senior partner, advising on strategy and the development of activities and operations.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] Considered already one of the biggest judicial errors in Brazil, Esteves has been fully vindicated and acquitted of all charges.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] On June 28, 2017, the Chief Justice of the Brazilian Supreme Court, Gilmar Mendes, referred André Esteves' case during the plenary session of the Supreme Court, "This is a fact of which we are witnesses.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] On September 1, 2017, the Federal Prosecution Service says it has not found evidence that Esteves committed the crime of obstruction of justice.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] "André was improperly involved in this process, the instruction proved this completely," said Antônio Carlos de Almeida Castro, Esteves' lawyer, on the request for acquittal.
[src:conservation-international/andré-esteves] On July 12, 2018, the Federal Court of Brasilia acquitted Esteves of the accusations of obstruction of justice for confirmation that there was insufficient evidence to corroborate the allegations.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In 1987, CI helped negotiate a debt-for-nature swap with Bolivia -- the first of its kind.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] It adopted biodiversity hotspots as a framework for setting conservation priorities in 1989, and created the Rapid Assessment Program in 1990 to carry out time-limited biodiversity surveys intended to inform conservation decisions.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] CI has also been involved in conservation finance and multilateral initiatives, including participation in the 2000 launch of the Critical Ecosystem Partnership Fund and the creation of the Global Conservation Fund.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Its public communications have included the celebrity-narrated campaign *Nature Is Speaking* (2014).
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Conservation International operates primarily through Conservation International Foundation, a U.S.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] 501(c)(3) nonprofit, and works through country programs and affiliated entities in multiple regions.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In fiscal year 2024, the foundation reported US$271 million in revenue and US$298 million in expenses, and CI reported more than 1,600 employees in 2025.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] The organization has faced criticism over aspects of project implementation and its engagement with corporate partners.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Conservation International was founded in 1987 by Peter Seligmann and Spencer Beebe.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Seligmann had worked at The Nature Conservancy and left that organization with a small staff and three board members to co-found CI with Beebe.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Although The Nature Conservancy had developed from a U.S. land trust model, CI's first major project was not a domestic land purchase but an international conservation-finance transaction linked to tropical protected areas.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] The organization's early niche combined international field projects, priority-setting for high-biodiversity regions, and financial mechanisms intended to direct conservation funding to tropical countries.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In July 1987, Conservation International and the Government of Bolivia signed a debt-for-nature swap agreement that has been described as the first of its kind.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Conservation International acquired US$650,000 of Bolivian external debt for US$100,000.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Bolivia provided the Beni Biological Station Biosphere Reserve with maximum legal protection, created three adjacent protected areas, and agreed to provide US$250,000 in local currency for management activities in the reserve.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] The transaction helped establish conservation finance as an important part of CI's institutional identity, linking biodiversity protection with financial tools, government commitments, and local-currency funding for protected-area management.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In 1989, Conservation International adopted biodiversity hotspots as a framework for setting conservation priorities.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] The hotspot approach emphasized regions with high concentrations of endemic species and substantial habitat loss, providing a global screening tool for directing limited conservation resources.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Together, the Bolivia debt swap and the adoption of hotspots reflected an early model built around international partnerships, biodiversity science, and finance rather than a single-country land-acquisition programme.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In the early 1990s, Conservation International halted direct-mail fundraising and expanded its programs using support from board members and foundation grants, including from the MacArthur Foundation.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In 1990, it entered its first corporate partnership, with McDonald's Corporation.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In 1990, Conservation International created the Rapid Assessment Program, a rapid biodiversity survey initiative intended to support conservation decision-making by generating biological information from field assessments.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In the mid-1990s, the organization expanded its fundraising strategies, with increased emphasis on foundations and wealthy individual donors.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In 1998, Conservation International scientists published an approach to setting conservation priorities that combined biodiversity hotspots and major tropical wilderness areas.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In 2000, Conservation International participated in the launch of the Critical Ecosystem Partnership Fund (CEPF), a partnership between the World Bank, the Global Environment Facility, and Conservation International that supports civil society conservation work in biodiversity hotspots.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] MacArthur Foundation joined CEPF as a partner in 2001, and the Government of Japan joined in 2002.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In 2001, Conservation International launched the Global Conservation Fund, which focuses on establishing the financial sustainability of specific protected areas.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In 2004, Starbucks launched Coffee and Farmer Equity (C.A.F.E.) Practices, a verification program developed by Starbucks, Conservation International, and SCS Global Services.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In 2014, Conservation International launched the public-awareness campaign *Nature Is Speaking* at SXSW Eco in Austin, Texas.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Sanjayan was named chief executive officer, succeeding Peter Seligmann, who remained chair of the board.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In August 2025, Sanjayan stepped down as CEO, and Daniela Raik was appointed interim chief executive officer while the board conducted a search for a permanent CEO.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In February 2026, Conservation International announced Sebastian Troëng as chief executive officer and named Lisa P.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Jackson interim chair of the board, succeeding Robert J.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Conservation International epidemiologist Dr.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Neil Vora was named to the 2025 Time 100 Next list.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In fiscal year 2024, CI reported expenditures of more than US$297 million.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Conservation International combines science-based priority setting with partnerships and financing mechanisms to support conservation at scale.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Conservationists use biodiversity hotspots as a screening tool for prioritizing conservation investment in regions that combine high concentrations of endemic species with extensive habitat loss.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] CI adopted the hotspots framework and has used it alongside other priority geographies such as major tropical wilderness areas and marine regions in its conservation work.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Researchers have debated hotspot-based prioritization, with critiques that concentrating resources on hotspots can overlook areas outside hotspot boundaries that still have high conservation value.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In 2008, Conservation International updated its mission and programme framing to emphasize the relationship between natural ecosystems and human well-being.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] The shift placed the organization within a broader movement in conservation science that treated biodiversity protection, ecosystem services, development, climate resilience and human livelihoods as linked objectives rather than separate policy areas.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] This approach was reflected in CI's growing emphasis on ecosystem services, nature-based solutions, conservation finance, climate adaptation, marine conservation and partnerships with governments, corporations, Indigenous peoples and local communities.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] The public message most closely associated with this change was that "people need nature to thrive".
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In practice, this framing moved CI's public communications away from appeals based mainly on protecting nature for its own sake and toward arguments that functioning ecosystems support food, freshwater, climate stability, health, livelihoods and economic security.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] The shift also helped connect the organization's older biodiversity-priority-setting work to newer programme areas such as blue carbon, freshwater assessment, climate adaptation and sustainable production landscapes.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] CI's best-known expression of this communications strategy was the 2014 campaign *Nature Is Speaking*, launched at SXSW Eco in Austin, Texas.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] The campaign used short films narrated by celebrity voices to personify elements of nature and to argue that nature would persist in some form, but that human societies depend on functioning natural systems.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Academic analysis of the campaign described it as a form of celebrity-mediated environmental communication that constructed nature as a speaking subject and linked concern for nature to concern for human futures.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] The people-centred framing also placed CI within debates over the so-called "new conservation" movement.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Supporters of human-well-being approaches argued that conservation strategies needed to integrate biodiversity protection with poverty, development, corporate behaviour, ecosystem services and the realities of human-dominated landscapes.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Critics argued that framing nature mainly through human benefits, economic value or corporate partnerships could weaken commitments to biodiversity protection and the intrinsic value of non-human life.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In CI's case, these debates overlapped with criticism of its corporate partnerships and of carbon-credit projects, which are discussed in the article's reception and criticism section.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Work with Indigenous peoples and local communities has been a recurring feature of Conservation International's programme model, especially where conservation depends on community governance, customary tenure, or long-term agreements over land and marine resources.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Questions about community consent, land tenure and benefit-sharing in some CI-linked projects are discussed further in the article's reception and criticism section.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] The *Betty and Gordon Moore Center for Science and Solutions* serves as Conservation International's research hub.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Its work links scientific research with field programmes, decision-support tools, monitoring, and applied conservation planning.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] The center works with CI field staff, traditional knowledge holders, communities, governments and other partners, and its staff structure includes roles focused on biodiversity science, nature-based solutions, blue carbon and science-for-impact functions.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] A long-running strand of CI's conservation science has been global priority-setting.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Published work associated with CI scientists includes frameworks for identifying biodiversity hotspots and major tropical wilderness areas as priority geographies for conservation investment.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] These approaches were intended to help direct limited conservation resources toward regions with high biodiversity value, high endemism, habitat loss or large remaining intact tropical ecosystems.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Field assessment has been another part of the organization's science programme.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] The Rapid Assessment Program, created in 1990, was designed to generate biological information from time-limited field assessments to support conservation decision-making.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Rapid Assessment Program reports have been used in country and regional programmes as baseline surveys for protected-area planning, marine zoning and biodiversity documentation, including later country-level work in places such as Timor-Leste, New Caledonia and Liberia.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Research on ecosystem services, climate adaptation and nature-based solutions has connected the Moore Center's science work to CI's field programmes.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Conservation scientists have contributed to research on ecosystem-based adaptation for smallholder farmers, including analysis of how agricultural practices can use biodiversity and ecosystem services to help farmers adapt to climate change.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] CI-affiliated scientists have also contributed to work quantifying the climate-mitigation potential of natural climate solutions, including conservation, restoration and improved land-management actions that increase carbon storage or avoid greenhouse-gas emissions.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Some research has been tied directly to monitoring and evaluation of field programmes.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] This type of work connects CI's science function to questions of programme design, impact measurement and accountability.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Decision-support tools associated with CI science include freshwater, ocean and ecosystem-service assessment frameworks.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] The Freshwater Health Index integrates social, hydrological and ecological dimensions of freshwater systems, combining indicators of ecosystem vitality, ecosystem services and governance to help water managers and stakeholders assess trade-offs in river basins.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] The Ocean Health Index, developed by an interdisciplinary research team that included Conservation International participation, assesses ocean health through ecological, social and economic benefits that oceans provide to people; it has been adapted in global and regional assessments.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Blue-carbon science forms another applied research area linked to the organization's climate and marine programmes.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In the wider article, this research area connects to CI-linked blue-carbon and coastal-resilience work in countries such as Singapore, Costa Rica, Ecuador and Fiji.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Conservation International has launched and supported a number of cross-border initiatives and campaigns that are managed centrally or implemented across multiple countries, alongside its country programs.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Conservation International has been associated with the use of conservation finance--financial mechanisms intended to mobilize and direct capital toward conservation, often by pairing conservation outcomes with durable funding streams and, in some cases, financial returns.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] CI's early history is linked to debt-for-nature swaps: in 1987 it helped negotiate a debt conversion with Bolivia that has been described as the first swap of its kind, directing local-currency resources toward protected-area creation and management funding.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] CI-linked programmes have also used performance-based approaches such as voluntary-market REDD+ finance linked to conservation agreements, and have participated in project-finance-for-permanence initiatives designed to secure long-term funding for protected-area systems.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Conservation International's climate-related work includes forest and rangeland carbon projects, coastal blue carbon initiatives, public climate-finance projects, and corporate climate-finance partnerships.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Forest and rangeland projects have used mechanisms such as REDD+, restoration finance and carbon credits to support protected-area management, conservation agreements and landscape restoration.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Examples include the Alto Mayo Protection Forest REDD+ project in Peru, the Chyulu Hills Carbon Project in Kenya, and a Prey Lang Wildlife Sanctuary REDD+ project in Cambodia under Japan's Joint Crediting Mechanism.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Blue-carbon work concerns carbon stored in coastal and marine ecosystems such as mangroves, seagrass meadows and salt marshes.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Conservation International-linked blue-carbon activities have included research, policy support, restoration planning and project finance in coastal regions.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] The Singapore-based International Blue Carbon Institute functions as a hub for blue-carbon research, implementation and capacity-building, while country-level projects have included mangrove and coastal-wetland work in Costa Rica, Ecuador and Fiji.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Some climate-related work has been financed through public environmental and climate funds.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Corporate climate finance has included carbon-credit purchases, restoration funds and blue-carbon research support, including Disney's retirement of credits from Alto Mayo, Apple's Restore Fund work with Conservation International, and Amazon's support for the International Blue Carbon Institute.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Criticism of offset-linked projects is discussed in the article's reception and criticism section.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Conservation International has acted as a project agency, accredited entity, implementing agency or executing partner in some projects financed by multilateral environmental funds.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Conservation International Foundation has served as an accredited entity for Green Climate Fund projects in Madagascar, Botswana and Ecuador, including sustainable-landscape, rangeland and mangrove-climate initiatives.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In Global Environment Facility programming, CI or its country programmes have also held project-agency, implementing or executing roles in projects in countries including Ecuador, Kenya, Liberia and Timor-Leste.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] These roles differ from CI's grantmaking and advocacy work because they involve formal responsibilities within public environmental-finance project structures.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Capacity building is a recurring part of Conservation International's work, alongside field conservation and finance.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Programmes have included internships, scholarships, practitioner support, environmental education and community training.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In Singapore, Conservation International's internship programme gives tertiary students experience in Asia-Pacific conservation work, and the MAC3 Conservation Scholarship supports postgraduate research on topics such as blue carbon and riparian ecosystems.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] At a broader institutional level, CI has also supported Indigenous leaders conservation fellowships and an Indigenous Peoples Negotiations Program intended to strengthen the ability of Indigenous peoples and local communities to participate in conservation and development negotiations.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Country and regional programmes have used capacity-building approaches in more localized forms.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In Timor-Leste, participatory learning tools and community nurseries have been used to support reforestation and natural-resource management, while Samoa's Guardians programme used the traditional voyaging canoe *Gaualofa* as a platform for hands-on environmental education in coastal districts.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Corporate partnerships have been part of Conservation International's operating model since the organization's early years, including work on supply-chain standards, conservation finance, climate initiatives, marketing partnerships and corporate sustainability advice.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In 1990, CI entered its first corporate partnership, with McDonald's, in work later described as focused on sustainable supply-chain issues and biodiversity conservation.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In 2004, Starbucks launched Coffee and Farmer Equity (C.A.F.E.) Practices, a verification programme developed with Conservation International and SCS Global Services to assess coffee production against economic, social and environmental criteria.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Conservation International Japan has also maintained corporate relationships with companies including Daikin and Mitsubishi Corporation, connected to corporate strategy, carbon and nature commitments, and cause-related communications.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In the 2020s, corporate and philanthropic partnerships have been linked to climate finance and marine-conservation initiatives.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Criticism of CI's corporate partnerships and offset-linked projects is discussed in the article's reception and criticism section.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] The Critical Ecosystem Partnership Fund (CEPF) is a multi-donor grantmaking initiative that supports civil-society conservation projects in biodiversity hotspots.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Conservation International participated in CEPF’s launch in 2000 as a partnership with the World Bank and the Global Environment Facility.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Conservation International's marine work has generally combined support for marine protected areas and protected-area networks with marine spatial planning, fisheries initiatives, blue carbon projects and long-term conservation finance.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Rather than focusing only on individual protected areas, several programmes have operated at seascape or national-waters scales, where conservation planning is linked to fisheries management, tourism, coastal livelihoods and durable funding.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Examples include the Phoenix Islands Protected Area in Kiribati, the Raja Ampat marine protected-area network in Indonesia, the Verde Island Passage network in the Philippines, and Samoa's national marine spatial-planning framework.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In several cases, governments or local institutions have designated or managed protected waters while CI and other partners have provided scientific surveys, planning support, financing, monitoring, or capacity-building.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Similar network-oriented approaches appear in the Verde Island Passage, where local-government alliances coordinated dozens of marine protected areas, and in Samoa, where the marine spatial plan incorporates new offshore protected areas and existing nearshore managed areas.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Fisheries and coastal-livelihood work forms another strand of CI's marine programme.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In Hawaiʻi, its programme has worked with partners including NOAA Fisheries on sustainable seafood and the utilisation of invasive reef fish, while in Palau it has supported planning and capacity-building linked to the Palau National Marine Sanctuary and the country's domestic fishing zone.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Coastal and blue-carbon initiatives link marine conservation to climate adaptation and mitigation by focusing on carbon-rich ecosystems such as mangroves and seagrass meadows.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] CI-linked projects have included mangrove and blue-carbon work in Costa Rica's Gulf of Nicoya and in Ecuador's coastal mangrove regions, as well as coastal-resilience work at Weg naar Zee in Suriname.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In Kiribati, the Phoenix Islands Protected Area was created in 2008 through a partnership between the Government of Kiribati, Conservation International and the New England Aquarium.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In Hawaiʻi, Conservation International’s programme has worked with partners including NOAA Fisheries on sustainable seafood and fisheries initiatives, including efforts to increase utilisation of invasive reef fish such as ta‘ape (bluestripe snapper).
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In Samoa, Conservation International's country programme has supported ocean governance and marine spatial planning through the Samoa Ocean Strategy and the Samoa Marine Spatial Plan.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] The Samoa Marine Spatial Plan 2025–2035 establishes an ocean-management system for Samoan waters, includes nine new fully protected marine protected areas, and incorporates existing nearshore managed areas.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] It is governed by a board of directors and led by a chief executive officer.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In February 2026, Sebastian Troëng was named chief executive officer and Lisa P.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Jackson was named interim chair of the board, succeeding Robert J.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Fisher; actor Harrison Ford is among the board members.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] CharityWatch reported that the foundation met its governance benchmarks, including an independent audit, a publicly available conflict-of-interest policy, and an independent board majority.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Beyond the U.S.-based Conservation International Foundation, CI's international network combines branch offices, field-based country programmes, and separately incorporated affiliates.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Not all units serve the same role: some are field-based national programmes, while others function mainly as partnership or support hubs.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Conservation International-Japan focuses on policy advocacy and government and corporate partnerships, whereas Conservation International Singapore began as a regional office and now supports nature markets, carbon-project development and the International Blue Carbon Institute from Singapore.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] In those filings, contributions and grants accounted for most reported revenue (91% in FY2024; 85% in FY2023), with smaller shares from investment income and other revenue.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] CharityWatch's analysis of consolidated statements for fiscal year 2023 estimated that government sources accounted for 0%-24% of the foundation's cash revenue.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] CI has raised support through foundation grants and corporate partnerships and has managed project-based conservation finance and climate and biodiversity funding, including programs connected to the Global Environment Facility and the Green Climate Fund.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p01] Some projects have used mechanisms such as trust funds and carbon finance linked to conservation agreements and other interventions.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International carries out much of its work through country programs and affiliated entities.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] The summaries below highlight country programs and affiliates; cross-border initiatives are described in *Global programs and initiatives*.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International has worked in Bolivia since 1987, focusing on Amazon conservation through protected-area support and conservation-finance initiatives.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In 1987 it helped implement a debt-for-nature swap described by the World Bank as the first of its kind, purchasing US$650,000 of Bolivian debt for US$100,000 and supporting protection and management funding for the Beni Biological Station Biosphere Reserve and three additional reserves.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] 2024 saw the creation of the Área Natural de Manejo Integrado El Gran Manupare in Sena (Pando Department), a protected area covering 452,639 hectares, with the process involving CI Bolivia’s technical team alongside local and municipal actors.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In Brazil, Conservation International began working in 1990 through Conservation International do Brasil.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In the Brazilian Amazon, it is an executing partner for the World Bank-led, Global Environment Facility-financed *Amazon Sustainable Landscapes Project*.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International also served as the executing agency for the UNDP-GEF project *Taking Deforestation Out of the Soy Supply Chain*, which focused on reducing deforestation linked to soy expansion in the MATOPIBA agricultural frontier.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International has worked in Colombia since 1991, carrying out programs that integrate conservation of natural resources with socio-economic development in partnership with government, academic, and civil-society actors.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In 2004 it was among the NGOs that signed a Tropical Forest Conservation Act debt-for-nature agreement that reduced Colombia’s debt to the United States by more than US$10 million in exchange for funding tropical-forest conservation projects.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In 2022, Conservation International joined partners launching *Herencia Colombia*, a project-finance-for-permanence initiative described as securing about US$245 million in public and private finance to support long-term management and expansion of Colombia’s protected-areas system.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In Costa Rica, Conservation International has worked for more than 35 years and its country programme focuses on ocean and coastal conservation and marine spatial planning.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] The programme also implements a pilot project under the Blue Carbon Facility of Agence française de développement (AFD) to support Costa Rica's National Blue Carbon Strategy and Action Plan, with fieldwork in mangroves in the Gulf of Nicoya.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International established its Ecuador country programme in 2001, focusing on biodiversity conservation and protected-area management in the Galápagos Islands and mainland Ecuador, including marine and coastal conservation and climate resilience.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] It has served as the Global Environment Facility agency for the Galápagos biosecurity and ecosystem restoration project *Safeguarding biodiversity in the Galapagos Islands by enhancing biosecurity and creating the enabling environment for the restoration of Galapagos Island ecosystems*.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International Foundation is the accredited entity for the Green Climate Fund project *Mangroves for climate: Public, Private and Community Partnerships for Mitigation and Adaptation in Ecuador*, approved in July 2024.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International has worked in Guyana since 1989, focusing on protected-area planning and community-based conservation in forest and coastal ecosystems.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In the Upper Takutu-Upper Essequibo region, it has supported the Wai Wai community of Konashen (Kanashen), which was later gazetted as the Kanashen Amerindian Protected Area (about 648,567 hectares) within Guyana’s National Protected Areas System.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] CI-Guyana has also been involved in supporting Guyana’s REDD+ forest monitoring through the national Monitoring, Reporting & Verification System (MRVS).
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In Mexico, Conservation International has worked since 1990, with a programme that includes coastal and marine conservation and landscape restoration with local and public partners.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In the 2020s, Conservation International has been involved in conservation-finance initiatives linked to Mexico's biodiversity targets, including the Global Biodiversity Framework Fund project *Mex30x30: Conserving Mexican biodiversity through the collective social participation approach*.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International has worked in Peru since 1989, focusing on Amazon forest conservation and protected-area management alongside community livelihoods and conservation finance.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In the Alto Mayo Protection Forest, it has used conservation agreements linked to voluntary-market REDD+ finance to support forest protection while providing participating households with technical assistance intended to improve livelihoods.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In Suriname, Conservation International helped establish the Central Suriname Nature Reserve, a 1,600,000-hectare protected area created in 1998 and inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2000.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] It supported the establishment of the Suriname Conservation Foundation, a conservation trust fund created in 1999 to help finance protected-area management.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Along the coast near Paramaribo, CI-Suriname and partners have worked on nature-based coastal protection at Weg naar Zee using sediment-trapping structures designed to promote mangrove regrowth and reduce erosion.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International has worked in Botswana since 1993, with programmes focused on biodiversity conservation and community-linked natural-resource management, including work associated with the Okavango Delta.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In the late 2000s, it participated in coordination and information-sharing forums associated with the Northern Botswana Human Wildlife Coexistence Project and worked with the Department of Wildlife and National Parks on the Western Kgalagadi Conservation Corridor.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In the 2020s, Conservation International became the accredited entity for the Green Climate Fund project *Ecosystem-Based Adaptation and Mitigation in Botswana's Communal Rangelands*.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International established its Kenya programme in 2014.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] The programme works on forest and rangeland conservation and restoration and supports climate-mitigation initiatives including REDD+.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In the Chyulu Hills landscape, it has supported community-based rangeland restoration for climate resilience and pastoral livelihoods.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International is the lead agency for the Global Environment Facility project *Advancing human-wildlife conflict management effectiveness in Kenya through an integrated approach*.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In May 2018, Conservation International and the Government of Liberia launched the Liberia Conservation Fund, an independent conservation fund intended to provide long-term financing for Liberia's protected areas.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In Madagascar, Conservation International has worked since 1990.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] The programme has focused on protected-area and forest-corridor management in eastern and south-eastern Madagascar, including the Ambositra–Vondrozo Forest Corridor (COFAV) and the Ankeniheny-Zahamena Corridor (CAZ).
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] CAZ links Zahamena National Park and Andasibe-Mantadia National Park and covers about 425,000 hectares (4,250 km2); a carbon-finance component was designed to generate verified emission reductions to help fund management costs and expand local livelihood opportunities.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In 2016, the Green Climate Fund approved *Sustainable Landscapes in Eastern Madagascar*, with Conservation International Foundation as the accredited entity.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation South Africa (CSA) is an independent affiliate of Conservation International established in 2010 and registered in South Africa as a Section 18A public benefit organisation.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] CSA supports rural economic development linked to biodiversity conservation, including sustainable veld management and grazing practices, and works with partners in landscapes such as Namakwa, the Eastern Grasslands and the Kruger to Canyons Biosphere Region.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Under the Mega Living Landscapes programme, CSA participates in collaborative platforms and implements landscape-planning, community, and durable-finance components, including work in the Namakwa and Eastern Grasslands landscapes and sustainable grazing initiatives in the Eastern Cape.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In Australia, Conservation International operates through the Conservation International Australia Environmental Trust, a registered charity (since 2021) endorsed as a Deductible gift recipient from 1 January 2024.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Through Mastercard’s Priceless Planet Coalition, Conservation International has supported Greening Australia’s forest-restoration plantings in New South Wales and Victoria, with 430,000 biodiverse native trees rolling out across the 2021–2022 planting seasons.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In Cambodia, Conservation International has worked since 2001 on forest conservation and protected-area management, including implementation of the Central Cardamom Protected Forest project with Cambodia’s Forestry Administration from July 2001 to September 2004.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In the Prey Lang Wildlife Sanctuary landscape, a REDD+ project registered under Japan's Joint Crediting Mechanism became operational in 2018 and is jointly implemented with Cambodia’s Ministry of Environment and Mitsui.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International began working in China in 2002, with early programme activity focused on mountain landscapes in southwest China (including parts of Yunnan and Sichuan).
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In the mid-2000s, the programme implemented activities linked to the Critical Ecosystem Partnership Fund (CEPF) and supported biodiversity surveys, conservation monitoring, and training for local and government staff, alongside community-based conservation and restoration work.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In Yunnan, it contributed to a payments-for-ecosystem-services pilot at and around the Lashihai Nature Reserve near Lijiang, testing compensation and incentive mechanisms linked to watershed services and conservation objectives.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International began working in Fiji in 2003, supporting biodiversity conservation and protected-area initiatives.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] A flagship effort has been support for the establishment of the Sovi Basin Conservation Area on Viti Levu, including development of a management plan and conservation-lease arrangements with landowners and partner institutions.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In 2005, landowners agreed to cancel a proposed logging concession in the Sovi Basin, and a conservation trust fund was developed to support long-term management and provide alternative income for landowners.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In Indonesia, Conservation International has worked since 2004, when it led a coalition that launched the Bird's Head Seascape Initiative in the Bird's Head Peninsula region of West Papua.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In 2024, a U.S.–Indonesia debt-for-nature swap targeted funding for conservation work in the Bird's Head Seascape and the Lesser Sunda–Banda seascape, including a contribution from Conservation International.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International Japan has worked on environmental conservation and policy advocacy since 1990, with activities including global conservation partnerships, advice to government and corporate partners, and work on sustainability and nature-related commitments.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Activities described for the programme include helping facilitate Japan's membership in the Critical Ecosystem Partnership Fund and supporting the establishment of Japan's first Key Biodiversity Areas in 2010.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International Japan was also an executing agency for the GEF-Satoyama Project, a Global Environment Facility project on biodiversity conservation and sustainable management in priority socio-ecological production landscapes and seascapes.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In 2018, Conservation International Japan began a project with Mitsui & Co. in Cambodia's Prey Lang Wildlife Sanctuary, linked to local management support, alternative livelihoods and carbon-credit finance under Japan's Joint Crediting Mechanism.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In New Caledonia, Conservation International established a local office in 2002, building on partnerships with the North Province that began in the 1990s.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Work has included a co-management conservation project around the Mont Panié reserve area initiated in 2003 with local partners (including the Dayu Biik association), alongside early invasive-mammal control trials begun in 2004.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In New Zealand (*Aotearoa*), Conservation International works through Conservation International Aotearoa, which supports iwi and Māori-led ocean initiatives and Pacific partnerships, including the Hinemoana Halo initiative.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Work in Aotearoa New Zealand has included policy research on coastal wetland blue carbon, including analysis related to blue-carbon crediting and market development.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] New Zealand’s Department of Conservation has partnered with Manta Watch NZ and Conservation International Aotearoa on research related to oceanic manta rays in New Zealand waters.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International began working in the Philippines in 1995.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Its programme combines terrestrial conservation in Palawan (including work associated with the Mount Mantalingahan protected landscape) with marine conservation and fisheries-management initiatives in priority seascapes such as the Verde Island Passage.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International has worked in Samoa since 2006, focusing on ocean planning and marine conservation.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In June 2025, Samoa legally adopted the *Samoa Marine Spatial Plan*, establishing nine fully protected marine protected areas covering 36,000 km2 (14,000 sq mi) and setting a target to fully protect 30% of Samoa’s ocean area while sustainably managing the remainder.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International Singapore operates as a Singapore-based programme and support hub rather than a primarily site-based country programme.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International was established in Singapore in 2009 as a regional office and later registered the Conservation International Singapore Conservation Trust; the trust received Institution of Public Character status in 2017.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Its work includes policy advice and finance for nature-based solutions, support for nature markets, and Asia-Pacific carbon project development through the Asia-Pacific Carbon Team.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] The International Blue Carbon Institute, based in Singapore, functions as a hub for blue-carbon research, implementation, capacity-building and practitioner exchange, with support from the Singapore Economic Development Board, Amazon, and other funders.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In Timor-Leste, Conservation International has been involved in protected-area and marine-conservation planning since at least 2009, when it was listed in a government planning report on the Nino Konis Santana National Park area.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In 2018, it was listed as the implementing agency for a Global Environment Facility-financed project intended to establish a national protected-area network and improve natural resource management in priority catchment corridors.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International–led reef surveys around Atauro Island have also been used in proposals to create a marine protected area for the island’s waters.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International has faced criticism in media and from advocacy organizations regarding aspects of its project implementation and its engagement with corporate partners.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In 2008, Conservation International faced criticism over its role in the Milne Bay Community Based Coastal and Marine Conservation Project in Milne Bay Province, Papua New Guinea.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International disputed the UNDP figure, said it had contributed US$2.3 million to the project, and denied financial impropriety while inviting a forensic audit.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] A later UNDP project document described the Milne Bay project as having been wound up early amid "fiscal and political controversy".
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Some environmental advocates argued that the episode illustrated how corporate partnerships could provide reputational benefits to companies.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In response, CI vice president Justin Ward told *HuffPost* that the video was misleading and not representative of CI's interactions with corporate partners, and said the organization did not offer image-management services and required potential partners to undergo a due diligence process.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Ward also said corporate partnerships accounted for less than 10% of CI's budget and argued that working with companies could be appropriate when relationships were transparent and funds were directed to conservation programs.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In 2013, Survival International and Botswana's Khwedom Council said that Basarwa (San) residents of the Ranyane settlement in Ghanzi District were being pressured to relocate.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] They linked the dispute to proposals for the Western Kgalagadi Conservation Corridor, a wildlife corridor project that *News24* reported had been developed with Conservation International.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] The *Guardian Sun* reported that the matter was before the High Court and subject to an interdict halting relocations; government spokesperson Jeff Ramsay denied that residents were being forced to move and said that relocations involved only households that had requested assistance.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] In December 2021, Sapiens magazine reported similar issues in Peru.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] At the Alto Mayo Conservation Initiative in Peru, CI had brokered the sale of carbon credits created from preserving forest land to the Disney Company to offset their cruise ships' activities.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Local members of the Rondero autonomous peasants group told reporters that 50 homes in the forest were demolished in 2021, while SERNANP reported that none of the homes were currently inhabited.
[src:conservation-international/conservation-international-p02] Conservation International stated that the demolitions were not funded by carbon credit revenues.
